The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic from this year on.
Maybe.
Perhaps the market for mobile phones in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
There, however, something is missing – a virtual operator who obliges traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
Because the Czech operators belong to the most dear in Europe we have already written many times about Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day ČTÚ confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularisation of roaming tariffs, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really want to start the clash.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even when we have three mobile networks and cover up to 100%.
Instead, mobile telofonia operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the Head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) , Pavel Dvořák, has often said that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities. (Of course it would be difficult to find other frequencies now.)
But there's still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which traditional operators should then react.
At the same time, even before the entrance of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile in the market, similar voices sounded in Britain like we did.
It has been shown, however, that the place for such operators is there and that they can be truly successful.
At the end of the day, for example, we must not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator managed to conquer more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking lies the Penta financial group to which in Czech Republic belongs among the other U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-shop.
In order to be able to work effectively, many fewer customers than a traditional operator are enough.
They do not carry behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low prices, which is often in balance with the offer of the narrowest services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking shows in Poland can be a pretty good move even the bet on a band-bersail not recently.
This operator is specifically aimed at men.
"The real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be affirmed by us as in Poland.
He doubts the press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services, it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not have many expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will take place rather in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman of the financial group Penta.
So he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything because they do not create any potential competitors.
For some time, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it's better first.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already been able to progress in negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl's spokesperson.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will have to have it maybe by the end of the year.
But for now around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we do not believe that there is space in the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefònika O2.
The specific nature of the Czech market also applies to other operators.
T-Mobil Martina Kemrová's press spokesman adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
He adds: "In the T-Mobile network a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it would be possible to consider it on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses his attention rather on reaching his 3G license requests.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators and this especially in the context of sharing of costs and infrastructures.
We consider this, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common fast mobile internet network."
The competent authorities - with the complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles around the creation U:fon testify that when operators tend to one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure against ČTú in the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to the public access information from the ČTú web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition environment of the mobile telephony market has been little strengthened beyond all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the typology of the mobile market in the Czech Republic it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put on him and above all on his high claims."
However, the attitude of mobile telephone operators is surprising because of the complete lack of interest on the part of Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, in relation to the whole problem, has taken its typical position.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, in the section for external relations ÚOHS, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not surprise.
On the other hand, the office which has to defend the interests of consumers, and on the other hand, the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and lower prices do not belong to the UOHS interest.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence, is raised on its own.
Equally as the same price of petrol for all gasolines is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so he has no greater responsibility for his behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points .
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTú, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition the only market.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has- ultimately logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators proceed in such a strange manner.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators face very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a pretty frequent trick with which ÚOHS is kept out of the whole thing.
This has already been found in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, he failed to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved Telecommunications Act was updated, despite the fact that many of these experts expected the situation to improve.
This is what UOHS representatives need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks
While we do not see the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of them even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These companies publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
Usually it's companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only those established.
The magic lies in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator appears as a classic business client, which orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a provision.
"If the cases you are talking about, of which we will be interested, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of the cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová replied.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a profit not indifferent and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
These also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the usual customers of mobile operators "
But this is supposed to be a strange minimum at Čtu.
In addition, another issue opens up for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has rights strong enough to expose similar activities and if it does not want you will not have to comply with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we're not more expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a considerable decrease in prices for services.
At the same time, practically in all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - market too small, limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries in these cases, regulators have intervened to defend not mobile telephone operators but their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then came to the creation of the first virtual operator and to him others have joined.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory organs throw each other all the case like a boiling potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But we don't throw away the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will really soon appear to us, the Czech mobile phone market will be back on its way.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only difficult ÚOHS could remain impassable to the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday the premier Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the recognition of the Czech State presented in a solemn way the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, chorus step and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz site you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already before he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"In the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the choir, have the clear dictionary, that the text is well understandable, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year on the 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov měj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It has acquired popularity and people have spontaneously made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the foundation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
