The Ministry of Internal Affairs requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, to install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a drunken state or if it does not blow into the device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the Procurator-General for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Seguridad dell'Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of the drivers reported more than once to drive in a state of drunkenness then return to drive the car.
Alcoholck would avoid it, because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the rate of alcohol in the breathed air and prevents the car from moving if the driver does not blow, or when a concentration of alcohol higher than that allowed is detected.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the prisoner.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices reduce up to 65% of the offences committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is calculated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: curbing these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in certain industrial and public vehicles.
