Speak in sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very nervously to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who speak while being asleep.
The first time that happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn't really matter.
This is a benign alteration of sleep defined as sleepiness.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have said that you have spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, nocturnal enuresis (piping in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress situations or overcrowding.
In any case, it is still a little studied phenomenon.
Even the intensity with which it appears is extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite occurs (scream, shout, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, the child should be observed and possibly a specialist should be consulted to see if there is any question that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a source of the situation.
We have said that this is benign alteration, therefore, there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g. if coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcit the child before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
