Meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as the Héma-Québec has become one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, seriously shocked by the blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, in February 1994 the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee to design a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still have confidence in the donation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood sampling and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary is convinced, however, that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle since its inception on 28 September 1998.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, tells the one who has been the president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know absolutely if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
Thus, one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelinau reports was that when there are doubts and there could be a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique appeared on the market for the detection of HIV: the tests of nucleic acid (TAN) which allowed the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, since the person has contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and thus not being able to detect them has thus diminished considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes every year between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples, it takes more than 24 years before a case of HIV is found with a transfusion.
I believe that today you can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the Hema-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Being the most aggressive cancer cure, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average constitute only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of penury are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
Now it is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frantic that there is hardly an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec distributes not only blood samples but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyeball and skin heart valves that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Hema-Quebec that manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth champion of cordon blood and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
You should begin to propose them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't have access to them," as Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
