The intelligent machine imitates the calabrone flight
What could be the best method to develop anti-contrast technologies if not to mimic the sensors of the obstacles that are in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented to CEATEC in Japan, the Calabrians gave the initial strategic insight to the Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-auto equipped with bees properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form a personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - explained to the exposure Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the bee view, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers have drawn on the laser telemetric idea to copy the function of the bee view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If it weren't for this, the auto robot wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Laboratory Mobility and the auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, in which the collision is now considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in an eye beater.
But unlike bees, the deviation can't go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to the bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and high energy density, which means that their duration is higher than those of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantity of intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some input in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so use only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don't need a memory of gigabyte or megabyte.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, provided for by Nissan, can be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Additional application possibilities can be represented by the unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leads to destination.
