The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion rescue plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
We have a confirmation from the New York Times yesterday informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favourable to federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to "the Washington ones" and the finance world, strong especially in the Central and South states.
The soul, for the record, that became prepotently alive with the vote I was saying at the beginning.
This, however, is just one example of the changes, of the major changes, which the current economic earthquake may well pre-announce or have already shown: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
Both in the USA and in Europe, the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time, which in the new climate are solidifying and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the refurbishment, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereignty category in relation to a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, yes, have close links with abroad, but which first of all see the very large size of the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also elected.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems largely out of play or not to have much to say: the overwhelming evidence is given by the European Union, which divides as usual between different interests and between the various state strategies, is unable to decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get close it is only the States that own economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things in the sixth place.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which no market and no international organisation can possibly ever have to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we noticed from a section that our future will have to deal increasingly with those very immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are nevertheless bound in an absolute way to a restricted space, to a territory.
So that those who are sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, those who are unlucky to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
However, I come to the second novelty that presages a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation into hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discretion for existing leadership, economic species, revealed so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together, something even deeper and in a certain disturbing sense: a discreet, an inoffer, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, it seems to be becoming more and more common in vast sectors of the population, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far at the height, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall acceptance of the term, to having made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimation of the traditional ruling classes and political assets, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolved" elections or in the sudden changes of the collective moods of these last and most recent times, from the conservative ascent in Austria and Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with you).
You have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it more and more difficult to understand, and thus to represent, what has not been taking shape since today in the deep strata of Western societies and that the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, potentially stirs up to dissipation.
In the face of all this talking about a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
