The figures provided by the Anec, the main association of the practitioners, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed the 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the biggest strike are mainly the salt in the main cities: 10 in less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna boasts 82 single cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to show that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" says Paolo Protti, President of Anec, "it is useful that new structures be built but we should guarantee the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the workers' fund: the government's pre-debt debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is ethically and morally shameful that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, has decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between Comune and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote single-sala cinemas in both the historical center and the suburbs.
Among the rules provided for are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for stopping and in some parking.
"It is an initiative that I like" notes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, however, that in order to counter the multi-x layer, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today the public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New cinema Paradise", which I had thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, there where I have experienced many shared emotions, so as not to see the signs from the dust I turn to the other side".
